namedPeople.description: Eric Joel Horvitz (/ˈhɔːrvɪts/) is an American computer scientist, and Technical Fellow at Microsoft, where he serves as director of Microsoft Research Labs, including research centers in Redmond, WA, Cambridge, Massachusetts, New York, NY, Montreal, Canada, Cambridge, UK, and Bangalore, India.
namedPeople.name: Eric Horvitz

transcript.text: We believe in the potential of AI to improve our lives and big and small ways. We need to make sure it's for the benefit of everyone.

For the first time, we're having machines moved into roles that have been the roles of human beings. Might these technologies have inadvertent effects on people and society? Do they align with people's values, their ethics? We need it to think through the implications for our company.
Approach that we take to developing and deploying our technology, making sure our principles are brought to life and that it empowers everyone and is inclusive and accessible for people.
Excellent, the job of the Office of responsible AI is to put our principles into practice by operationalising ethics across the company.
The Ethics Committee is responsible for deliberating about hard new questions.

We have to think through what it means to detect bias, make our systems more fair, to detect errors and blind spots in our technologies, and on thinking through the kinds of advice we give to other organizations on to our leaders where technology can impose on privacy and human rights. Responsibility is at the core world. Learning everyday about this new role of responsible computing.
We need to translate academic thought to language that.
Engineers and salespeople are familiar with our customers, have grappling with many of the same issues. It's incumbent on us to share what we learned.
It's about trying to do better everyday working with our customers and outside agencies to develop processes and deliver responsible computing technologies to the world.
